# SECTION 2: DEEP THEORETICAL ANALYSIS & KTU HIGH-YIELD FORMULA SHEET

## 2.1 Operational Logic — How a DLL Functions

The DLL operates on **three foundational operations** that drive every higher-level manipulation:

### A. The Traversal Logic (Bidirectional Movement)

**Forward Traversal (Head → Tail):**
1. Start at `head` (the entry point of the list).
2. Process `head->data`.
3. Move to `head->next`. If non-NULL, repeat from step 2.
4. Stop when `next` is `NULL` (tail reached).

**Backward Traversal (Tail → Head):**
1. Start at `tail` (must be tracked separately, or recovered via `head` traversal).
2. Process `tail->data`.
3. Move to `tail->prev`. If non-NULL, repeat from step 2.
4. Stop when `prev` is `NULL` (head reached).

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Insight:** Many students lose marks by forgetting that the `tail` pointer is **not automatic** in a DLL — the programmer must either maintain it explicitly or recover it by traversing from `head` (an O($n$) operation).

### B. The Insertion Logic (4 Pointer Reassignments)

When inserting a new node `N` between node `A` (left neighbor) and node `B` (right neighbor), exactly **4 pointer updates** are needed:

$$N.\text{next} = B, \quad N.\text{prev} = A, \quad A.\text{next} = N, \quad B.\text{prev} = N$$

If insertion is at the **head**, the steps reduce to 3 (B is `head`, A does not exist; we update `head->prev = N` and `head = N`).

### C. The Deletion Logic (2 Pointer Reassignments + Free)

When deleting node `N` between `A` and `B`:

$$A.\text{next} = B, \quad B.\text{prev} = A, \quad \text{free}(N)$$

This is the **killer feature** of DLL — if you already hold a pointer to `N`, deletion is **O(1)**. In a singly linked list, you would need the predecessor node, forcing an O($n$) search.

## 2.2 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet (Time & Space Complexity)

| Operation | Time Complexity (Best / Average / Worst) | Space Complexity | Why? |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Insertion at Head** | $O(1)$ | $O(1)$ | Only 3 pointer updates needed; no traversal |
| **Insertion at Tail** | $O(1)$ with tail pointer, else $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ | Need to reach tail; or jump directly if `tail` is maintained |
| **Insertion at Position $k$** | $O(k)$ | $O(1)$ | Must traverse $k-1$ nodes from head |
| **Deletion at Head** | $O(1)$ | $O(1)$ | Update `head = head->next`; set new head's `prev = NULL` |
| **Deletion at Tail** | $O(1)$ with tail pointer, else $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ | Direct access via tail; or traverse if tail not maintained |
| **Deletion at Position $k$** | $O(k)$ | $O(1)$ | Traverse to find node, then O(1) unlinking |
| **Forward Traversal** | $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ | Visit each node once |
| **Backward Traversal** | $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ | Use `prev` links |
| **Search** | $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ | Linear scan; no random access |
| **Total Space for $n$ nodes** | — | $O(n)$ | Each node stores 2 pointers + data |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Use `\vert` for absolute value bars in KTU answer sheets** (e.g., write $\vert x \vert$ instead of $\vert x \vert$ to avoid formatting issues in digital submissions).

## 2.3 Comparison: Singly vs Doubly Linked List (High-Yield for KTU)

| Feature | Singly Linked List (SLL) | Doubly Linked List (DLL) |
|---|---|---|
| Pointers per node | 1 (`next`) | 2 (`next`, `prev`) |
| Memory per node | Smaller | Larger (~1.6× for 64-bit ptrs) |
| Forward traversal | Yes | Yes |
| Backward traversal | No (must re-traverse from head) | Yes (direct) |
| Deletion of known node | $O(n)$ (need predecessor) | $O(1)$ (direct unlink) |
| Insertion at known position | $O(1)$ (if predecessor known) | $O(1)$ |
| Code complexity | Lower | Higher (4 pointer updates) |
| Typical use case | Stacks, simple queues | LRU Cache, Deques, navigation history |

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Applications

1. **Web Browser History (Back/Forward Buttons):** The "Back" button uses `prev` traversal; "Forward" uses `next`. Chrome's internal implementation uses DLL for tab navigation.
2. **LRU Cache (Least Recently Used):** When a cache entry is accessed, it is moved to the head of a DLL in $O(1)$. When the cache is full, the tail is evicted in $O(1)$.
3. **Undo/Redo Operations in Editors:** Each state is a node; `prev` = undo stack, `next` = redo stack.
4. **Music Player Playlists:** Next/Previous song navigation uses `next`/`prev` pointers.
5. **Operating System Process Scheduling:** The Doubly Linked List is used in the Linux kernel for maintaining task lists (`list_head` structure in `<linux/list.h>`).

