# SECTION 3: STEP-BY-STEP DERIVATIONS & ALGORITHMIC ANALYSIS

## 3.1 Derivation of the "Total NULL Pointer Count" in a DLL of $n$ Nodes

We will rigorously derive the number of `NULL` pointers in a DLL of $n$ nodes.

**Step 1 — Define the count function.**
Let $C(n)$ denote the total number of `NULL` pointer fields across all $n$ nodes in a DLL.

**Step 2 — Count pointer fields.**
Each node $n_i$ contains exactly **2 pointer fields**: $n_i.\text{next}$ and $n_i.\text{prev}$.

$$\text{Total pointer fields} = 2n$$

**Step 3 — Identify boundary conditions.**
In a non-circular DLL:
- Node $n_0$ (head) has $n_0.\text{prev} = \text{NULL}$.
- Node $n_{n-1}$ (tail) has $n_{n-1}.\text{next} = \text{NULL}$.
- All other pointer fields are non-NULL (they point to a valid neighbor).

**Step 4 — Compute $C(n)$.**

$$C(n) = \underbrace{1}_{n_0.\text{prev}} + \underbrace{1}_{n_{n-1}.\text{next}} = 2$$

Therefore:

$$\boxed{C(n) = 2 \quad \text{for all} \quad n \ge 1}$$

> **Verification:** For $n = 1$, the single node has $n_0.\text{prev} = \text{NULL}$ and $n_0.\text{next} = \text{NULL}$, so $C(1) = 2$. ✓

**Step 5 — Extension to Circular DLL.**
If the DLL is circular, then no pointer is NULL (head's `prev` points to tail, tail's `next` points to head). Hence $C_{\text{circular}}(n) = 0$.

## 3.2 Derivation of Time Complexity for "Delete Last Node" Operation

**Problem:** Find the time complexity of deleting the tail node from a DLL of $n$ nodes, **without** a maintained `tail` pointer.

**Step 1 — Cost of locating the tail.**
Without a `tail` pointer, we must traverse from `head`:

$$T_{\text{traverse}}(n) = \sum_{i=0}^{n-1} 1 = n \quad \text{visits}$$

This is $O(n)$.

**Step 2 — Cost of pointer reassignment.**

$$T_{\text{reassign}} = 2 \text{ operations (set new tail's next to NULL, update second-last's next pointer)} = O(1)$$

Wait — correction. In DLL deletion, we set the predecessor's `next = NULL` and free the tail. The second operation involves only 2 pointer updates. So:

$$T_{\text{reassign}} = O(1)$$

**Step 3 — Total cost.**

$$T_{\text{total}} = T_{\text{traverse}} + T_{\text{reassign}} = n + 2 = O(n)$$

**Step 4 — Comparison with SLL.**
For a SLL, deletion of the tail is $O(n)$ (traversal) plus the same pointer update cost. So the **asymptotic** complexity is the same; however, in a SLL you must track the predecessor **during** traversal, while in DLL the `prev` pointer is stored. The DLL still wins for $O(1)$ deletion of an **arbitrary known node**.

## 3.3 Worked Example — Insertion at the Middle of a DLL (Numerical Trace)

**Problem:** Given the DLL `10 ⇄ 20 ⇄ 30 ⇄ 40`, insert node `25` after node `20`.

**Initial State (Memory Diagram):**

$$H \rightarrow [10 \mid \text{NULL} \leftrightarrow \text{NEXT}] \leftrightarrow [20] \leftrightarrow [30] \leftrightarrow [40 \leftrightarrow \text{NULL}] \leftarrow T$$

**Step 1 — Locate insertion point.**
Traverse from `head` until `current->data == 20`. This takes $O(2)$ operations (visiting nodes 10 and 20).

**Step 2 — Identify neighbors.**
- $A =$ node(20), so $A.\text{next} =$ node(30) = $B$.
- $N =$ new node(25).

**Step 3 — Perform the 4 pointer updates (in safe order to avoid orphaning):**

$$N.\text{next} = A.\text{next} = B$$
$$N.\text{prev} = A$$
$$B.\text{prev} = N$$
$$A.\text{next} = N$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Order matters!** If you set $A.\text{next} = N$ **before** saving $B = A.\text{next}$, you will lose the reference to node(30) and the list will be corrupted. KTU examiners specifically look for this ordering in answer scripts.

**Step 4 — Final state:**

$$H \rightarrow [10] \leftrightarrow [20] \leftrightarrow [25] \leftrightarrow [30] \leftrightarrow [40] \leftarrow T$$

**Verification by traversal:** Forward → 10, 20, 25, 30, 40 ✓ | Backward → 40, 30, 25, 20, 10 ✓

## 3.4 Worked C Code — Complete DLL with All Operations

Below is a complete, KTU-board-ready C program implementing a DLL with insertion (head, tail, after a given node) and deletion (head, tail, by value) operations.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

// Node definition for Doubly Linked List
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* next;
    struct Node* prev;
};

// Function to create a new node
struct Node* createNode(int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    if (newNode == NULL) {
        printf("Memory allocation failed!\n");
        exit(1);
    }
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = NULL;
    newNode->prev = NULL;
    return newNode;
}

// Insert at the head of the DLL
void insertAtHead(struct Node** head, int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = createNode(data);
    if (*head != NULL) {
        (*head)->prev = newNode;
        newNode->next = *head;
    }
    *head = newNode;
}

// Insert at the tail of the DLL
void insertAtTail(struct Node** head, int data) {
    struct Node* newNode = createNode(data);
    if (*head == NULL) {
        *head = newNode;
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = *head;
    while (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    temp->next = newNode;
    newNode->prev = temp;
}

// Delete a node with a given value
void deleteNode(struct Node** head, int key) {
    if (*head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node* temp = *head;
    // Traverse to find the node
    while (temp != NULL && temp->data != key) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    if (temp == NULL) {
        printf("Key %d not found.\n", key);
        return;
    }
    // Update predecessor's next pointer
    if (temp->prev != NULL) {
        temp->prev->next = temp->next;
    } else {
        // Deleting the head
        *head = temp->next;
    }
    // Update successor's prev pointer
    if (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp->next->prev = temp->prev;
    }
    free(temp);
    printf("Deleted %d successfully.\n", key);
}

// Forward traversal
void traverseForward(struct Node* head) {
    struct Node* temp = head;
    printf("Forward: ");
    while (temp != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", temp->data);
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

// Backward traversal
void traverseBackward(struct Node* head) {
    if (head == NULL) return;
    struct Node* temp = head;
    // Move to tail first
    while (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("Backward: ");
    while (temp != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", temp->data);
        temp = temp->prev;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    struct Node* head = NULL;

    insertAtTail(&head, 10);
    insertAtTail(&head, 20);
    insertAtTail(&head, 30);
    insertAtHead(&head, 5);
    insertAtTail(&head, 40);

    traverseForward(head);   // Output: 5 10 20 30 40
    traverseBackward(head);  // Output: 40 30 20 10 5

    deleteNode(&head, 20);
    traverseForward(head);   // Output: 5 10 30 40

    deleteNode(&head, 5);
    traverseForward(head);   // Output: 10 30 40

    return 0;
}
```

> [!TIP]
> **KTU Practical Exam Tip:** Always free the deleted node's memory to avoid memory leaks. Examiners check for `free(temp)` calls. Missing this will cost you **2 marks** in the lab evaluation.

