# SECTION 5: KTU 2024 SCHEME EXAMINATION QUESTION BANK & TOPIC RECAP

## 5.1 PART A QUESTIONS (3 Marks Each)

### Q1. Define a Doubly Linked List. Mention any two advantages over a singly linked list.
**[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023]**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

A Doubly Linked List (DLL) is a linear data structure in which each node contains three fields: a **data field**, a **next pointer** to the successor, and a **prev pointer** to the predecessor. The first node's `prev` and the last node's `next` are set to `NULL`.

**Two advantages over a Singly Linked List:**

1. **Bidirectional Traversal:** A DLL can be traversed in both forward and backward directions, whereas a SLL only allows forward traversal.
2. **Efficient Deletion:** Deleting a node from a DLL takes $O(1)$ time if a pointer to the node is already available, while in a SLL, the predecessor must first be found, making deletion $O(n)$.

*(Marks distribution: Definition = 1, Each advantage = 1, Total = 3)*

### Q2. State the number of NULL pointers in a Doubly Linked List of $n$ nodes. Justify.
**[KTU University Exam — May 2024]**

**Model Answer (3 Marks):**

The number of NULL pointers in a non-circular Doubly Linked List of $n$ nodes is **2**.

**Justification:** Each of the $n$ nodes contains 2 pointer fields, giving a total of $2n$ pointers. Out of these, only 2 pointers are assigned `NULL`:
- The `prev` pointer of the head node (1st node).
- The `next` pointer of the tail node ($n$-th node).

All other $2n - 2$ pointers point to valid neighboring nodes. Hence, the count is exactly **2** for any $n \ge 1$.

## 5.2 PART B QUESTIONS (14 Marks Each — Module Internal Choice)

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning:** For 14-mark DLL questions, students commonly lose marks in the following ways:
> 1. **Drawing diagrams without arrow direction labels** for `next` and `prev` — lose 2 marks.
> 2. **Skipping pointer ordering in insertion/deletion** — using wrong sequence causes list corruption; lose 2 marks.
> 3. **Forgetting to update `head` pointer** when inserting/deleting at head — lose 1 mark.
> 4. **Not mentioning time complexity** for each operation — lose 1 mark.
> 5. **Memory leak** — failing to `free()` deleted nodes in C code — lose 1 mark.

---

### QUESTION A (14 Marks)
**[KTU University Exam — Dec 2022]**

**(a)** Explain the structure of a Doubly Linked List node with a neat diagram. Write a C function to insert a node at the **end** of a Doubly Linked List. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a C function to delete a node with a given value from a Doubly Linked List. Explain the time complexity. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### Model Solution for Q.A (a) — 7 Marks

**Node Structure with Diagram (3 Marks):**

A DLL node is a structure with three fields:

```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node* prev;
    struct Node* next;
};
```

**Diagram:**

```
        (Head)
           |
           v
       +----+----+----+
   <-- |prev| 10 |next| -->
       +----+----+----+
              |
              v
       +----+----+----+
   <-- |prev| 20 |next| -->
       +----+----+----+
              |
              v
           (Tail)
            NULL
```

**C Function — Insert at End (4 Marks):**

```c
void insertAtEnd(struct Node** head, int data) {
    // Step 1: Allocate and initialize new node
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = NULL;
    newNode->prev = NULL;

    // Step 2: If list is empty, new node becomes head
    if (*head == NULL) {
        *head = newNode;
        return;
    }

    // Step 3: Traverse to the last node
    struct Node* temp = *head;
    while (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    // Step 4: Update pointers (4 pointer updates)
    temp->next = newNode;     // Old tail's next = new node
    newNode->prev = temp;     // New node's prev = old tail
    // newNode->next is already NULL from Step 1
    // temp->prev remains unchanged
}
```

**Time Complexity:** $O(n)$ where $n$ is the number of nodes (due to traversal to the end).

---

#### Model Solution for Q.A (b) — 7 Marks

**C Function — Delete a Node by Value (5 Marks):**

```c
void deleteNode(struct Node** head, int key) {
    // Step 1: Handle empty list
    if (*head == NULL) {
        printf("List is empty.\n");
        return;
    }

    // Step 2: Traverse to find the node with given key
    struct Node* temp = *head;
    while (temp != NULL && temp->data != key) {
        temp = temp->next;
    }

    // Step 3: If key not found
    if (temp == NULL) {
        printf("Key %d not found in the list.\n", key);
        return;
    }

    // Step 4: Update predecessor's next pointer
    if (temp->prev != NULL) {
        temp->prev->next = temp->next;
    } else {
        // Deleting the head node
        *head = temp->next;
    }

    // Step 5: Update successor's prev pointer
    if (temp->next != NULL) {
        temp->next->prev = temp->prev;
    }

    // Step 6: Free the memory
    free(temp);
    printf("Node with value %d deleted.\n", key);
}
```

**Time Complexity Analysis (2 Marks):**

| Step | Operation | Complexity |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Empty list check | $O(1)$ |
| 2 | Search for key (worst case: traverse entire list) | $O(n)$ |
| 3 | Not-found check | $O(1)$ |
| 4–5 | Pointer reassignments (constant number) | $O(1)$ |
| 6 | Memory deallocation | $O(1)$ |
| **Total** | | **$O(n)$** |

> **Conclusion:** The overall time complexity of deletion by value is **$O(n)$** dominated by the search step. However, if a direct pointer to the node is already known, deletion becomes **$O(1)$** — the key advantage of DLLs.

