### QUESTION B (14 Marks) — *Alternative Choice*
**[KTU University Exam — May 2023]**

**(a)** Compare Singly Linked List and Doubly Linked List with respect to memory, traversal, and deletion. Write a C function to insert a node at the **beginning** of a Doubly Linked List. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Given the Doubly Linked List `5 ⇄ 15 ⇄ 25 ⇄ 35 ⇄ 45`, perform the following operations step by step (show the list state after each):
  - (i) Insert `10` at the beginning. **(2 Marks)**
  - (ii) Insert `40` after `35`. **(2 Marks)**
  - (iii) Delete `25` from the list. **(3 Marks)**

---

#### Model Solution for Q.B (a) — 7 Marks

**Comparison Table (4 Marks):**

| Criterion | Singly Linked List | Doubly Linked List |
|---|---|---|
| **Memory per node** | 1 pointer (~8 bytes) | 2 pointers (~16 bytes) |
| **Forward traversal** | Supported | Supported |
| **Backward traversal** | Not directly supported | Supported via `prev` |
| **Deletion of known node** | $O(n)$ (need predecessor) | $O(1)$ (direct unlink) |
| **Insertion complexity** | Simple (1 pointer update) | Moderate (4 pointer updates) |
| **Code complexity** | Lower | Higher |
| **Use cases** | Stacks, simple queues | LRU cache, deques, browser history |

**C Function — Insert at Beginning (3 Marks):**

```c
void insertAtBeginning(struct Node** head, int data) {
    // Step 1: Allocate new node
    struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = data;
    newNode->next = NULL;
    newNode->prev = NULL;

    // Step 2: If list is not empty, update old head's prev
    if (*head != NULL) {
        (*head)->prev = newNode;
        newNode->next = *head;
    }

    // Step 3: Update head pointer
    *head = newNode;
}
```

**Time Complexity:** $O(1)$ — only 3 pointer operations, no traversal.

